# 🔹 8. Ternary Operator

```python
# Single-line if-else

a = 10
b = 20

minimum = a if a < b else b

print(minimum)
```

---

## ✅ Output

```python
10
```

---

## 📌 Syntax

```python
value_if_true if condition else value_if_false
```

---

## 🎯 Interview Questions

* What is ternary operator?
* Why use ternary instead of if-else?
(A ternary operator is a concise way to write an if-else statement in a single line. It improves readability for simple conditional assignments.)

---

# 🔹 9. Operator Precedence

```python
# Multiplication has higher precedence

expr = 10 + 20 * 30

print(expr)
```

---

## ✅ Output

```python
610
```

---

## 📌 Common Precedence Order

| Priority | Operators   |
| -------- | ----------- |
| Highest  | ()          |
|          | **          |
|          | *, /, //, % |
|          | +, -        |
| Lowest   | and, or     |

---

## 🎯 Interview Questions

* What is operator precedence?
* Which operator executes first?
(Operator precedence is the rule that determines the order in which operators are evaluated in an expression. Operators with higher precedence execute before operators with lower precedence.)

---

# 🔹 10. Operator Associativity

```python
print(100 / 10 * 10)

print(5 - 2 + 3)

print(2 ** 3 ** 2)
```

---

## ✅ Output

```python
100.0
6
512
```

---

## 📌 Associativity Rules

| Direction    | Operators  |
| ------------ | ---------- |
| Left → Right | +, -, *, / |
| Right → Left | **         |

---

## 🎯 Interview Questions

* Why is `2 ** 3 ** 2 = 512` ?
* What is associativity?
(Associativity defines the order in which operators of the same precedence are evaluated, either left-to-right or right-to-left.)
